<li id="comment-3287" class="comment byuser comment-author-dimas bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 role-administrator user-dimas entry-author has-avatar">
<a href="http://farinspace.com" rel="external nofollow" title="Dimas"><img alt='Dimas' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/b629ed1cba20572343371a447a886b4a?s=80&#038;r=r' srcset='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/b629ed1cba20572343371a447a886b4a?s=160&amp;r=r 2x' class='avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /></a><div class="comment-meta comment-meta-data"><span class="comment-author vcard"><cite class="fn" title="http://farinspace.com"><a href="http://farinspace.com" title="Dimas" class="url" rel="external nofollow">Dimas</a></cite></span><!-- .comment-author .vcard --> <span class="published"><abbr class="comment-date" title="Friday, August 20th, 2010, 8:51 am">August 20, 2010</abbr> at <abbr class="comment-time" title="Friday, August 20th, 2010, 8:51 am">8:51 am</abbr></span> | <a class="permalink" href="http://www.farinspace.com/multiple-wordpress-wysiwyg-visual-editors/#comment-3287" title="Permalink to comment 3287">Permalink</a>  </div>
<div class="comment-text">
<p>Adam, thanks for the tip. This has given me more insight into the WordPress TineMCE editor usage.</p>
<p>However, my initial tests with <code>the_editor()</code> function were not very successful. Although I was able to get a second editor on the page, the switching between HTML and Visual did not work as expected. </p>
<p>When looking at the function, defined in <code>/wp-includes/general-template.php</code>, it seems that there are hard coded element IDs which I think cause the conflict (this also signifies to me that this function is more of an internal WordPress function).</p>
<p>Another thing to note, is that the WordPress <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Filter_Reference#Rich_Text_Editor_Filters" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-comment', 'http://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Filter_Reference#Rich_Text_Editor_Filters', 'filters for TinyMCE']);" rel="nofollow">filters for TinyMCE</a>, seem to only be setup to affect the main editor.</p>
<p>Anyway, do I think a developer can work around certain issues, of course &#8230; do I think it&#8217;ll be easy &#8230; umm, not really, it&#8217;ll take a little bit of time and figuring things out.</p>
</div><!-- .comment-text -->
