<li id="comment-8072" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 reader has-avatar">
<a href="http://friendlywebconsulting.com/" rel="external nofollow" title="Michelle"><img alt='Michelle' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/ab72597062368a7110b1c1510eb9f3a7?s=80&#038;r=r' srcset='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/ab72597062368a7110b1c1510eb9f3a7?s=160&amp;r=r 2x' class='avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /></a><div class="comment-meta comment-meta-data"><span class="comment-author vcard"><cite class="fn" title="http://friendlywebconsulting.com/"><a href="http://friendlywebconsulting.com/" title="Michelle" class="url" rel="external nofollow">Michelle</a></cite></span><!-- .comment-author .vcard --> <span class="published"><abbr class="comment-date" title="Friday, January 7th, 2011, 1:32 pm">January 7, 2011</abbr> at <abbr class="comment-time" title="Friday, January 7th, 2011, 1:32 pm">1:32 pm</abbr></span> | <a class="permalink" href="http://www.farinspace.com/multiple-wordpress-wysiwyg-visual-editors/#comment-8072" title="Permalink to comment 8072">Permalink</a>  </div>
<div class="comment-text">
<p>Never mind &#8211; I figured it out. (Apologies in advance &#8211; I  cannot figure out how to get both html and php to display together in these comments using the pre tag so I&#8217;m just including the key bits of php. ) </p>
<p>To get the meta fields to remember paragraph and line breaks, use wpautop like so in the meta.php template in the textarea&#8217;s value attribute:</p>
<pre lang="php" line="1" escaped="true">
echo wpautop($metabox-&gt;get_the_value('field_name'));
</pre>
<p>And like so in your custom theme templates to get things to display correctly:</p>
<pre lang="php" line="1" escaped="true">
echo wpautop($custom_metabox-&gt;get_the_value('field_name'));
</pre>
<p>Hope this helps someone!</p>
</div><!-- .comment-text -->
</li><!-- .comment -->
