<li id="comment-17546" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 reader has-avatar">
<img alt='Sylvain' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/63afffdde334cfd119ff84c13ec33ef4?s=80&#038;r=r' srcset='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/63afffdde334cfd119ff84c13ec33ef4?s=160&amp;r=r 2x' class='avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /><div class="comment-meta comment-meta-data"><span class="comment-author vcard"><cite class="fn">Sylvain</cite></span><!-- .comment-author .vcard --> <span class="published"><abbr class="comment-date" title="Friday, September 2nd, 2011, 2:25 am">September 2, 2011</abbr> at <abbr class="comment-time" title="Friday, September 2nd, 2011, 2:25 am">2:25 am</abbr></span> | <a class="permalink" href="http://www.farinspace.com/multiple-wordpress-wysiwyg-visual-editors/#comment-17546" title="Permalink to comment 17546">Permalink</a>  </div>
<div class="comment-text">
<p>My solution is :</p>
<p>Install the plugin <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/tinymce-advanced/" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-comment', 'http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/tinymce-advanced/', 'TinyMCE Advanced']);" rel="nofollow">TinyMCE Advanced</a> and check &#8220;Stop removing the  and  tags when saving and show them in the HTML editor&#8221;.</p>
<p>Juste show the content of your textarea with :<br />
<code><br />
echo $mb-&gt;get_the_value();<br />
</code><br />
It works fine for me.</p>
</div><!-- .comment-text -->
</li><!-- .comment -->
